This is going to be a regular thing for me for sure! I'm in love with making crepes in general and this is a keeper method. I substituted all the brandy with Disarronno Amaretto and it was stupendous. Very sweet though.

Rating: 4
This is my go-to recipe for crepes! It does come out watery at first, but after sitting in the fridge overnight or for at least 2 hours, it become slightly thicker. I also used 2 pans when making them. I scoped the mixture into a small pan first then spread it around. It's easy as the mixture is thin, which should be the right consistency- you don't want a pancake. After afew minutes (when u see some bubbles), you flip it over onto a bigger hot pan. There's no need to use spatula! I made the mistake of placing the crepes in the oven to keep them warm as I went about making the crepes,... and some of the edges dried out. On my second attempt, I placed a lid over the crepes (when they are in the oven). Problem solved. You get warm and slightly moist crepes that are to die for! As strawberries are in season, I made a compote of strawberries/butter/sugar sauce to go with the crepes.

Rating: 4
Excellent! No need to adjust amounts as others instruct. Simply make the night before and leave the batter in the blender in the fridge. Letting crepe batter rest is traditional and serves a purpose: the flour will absorb more liquid which both thickens the batter a bit and affects how it cooks. If you let it rest overnight this batter handles beautifully in a crepe pan and you can't taste the liquor---as someone else mentioned it just deepens the buttery flavor. I think this is the best sweet/breakfast crepe batter I have ever tasted (and I've eaten a lot of crepes in France).

