Rating: 4
I found this recipe accidentally while looking for something to do with 4 kiwi I got in my weekly "farm box". The reviews were so unwaveringly positive that I couldn't wait to go shopping for all the right ingredients. Like others who have written here, I used what I had and made substitutes as needed -- with absolutely no noticeable effect on the final product. These were amazing!! I will try them again according to recipe, but please know you can have a great crepe with whatever you have on hand. Of course, you must have the eggs! Here are my substitutes/changes: --unsweetened vanilla soy milk for milk --3 Tbs melted butter instead of 5 Tbs --irish whiskey for brandy/cognac (only had about 1/3 cup - added extra vanilla to make up liquid) --"Zero"(erythritol,fermented sugar, zero calories) for regular sugar --Trader Joe' white 100% whole week flour for all purpose flour I had only one cast iron skillet, so used one of my nonstick ironclad skillets as a second to keep the process moving along. Both worked beautifully - no particular advantage to the cast iron except maybe a bit more even browning. I cut up fresh fruit--strawberries, two of the kiwi, raspberries and banana. I added the juice of half a lime to the mixture and cut the fruit up pretty small. Also, I added a sprinkle of Zero to bring out the juices. Finally, Trader Joe's organic, low-fat vanilla yogurt made a delisious "sauce" and may be a bit lower in calories and saturated fat than whipped cream. It is rare that something tried for the first time comes out so well - particularly with so many substitutions. Please try this - it is well worth the little extra prep required and would be a great treat for company.

